The opponent's calculation method is fundamentally incorrect because it treats 180 as the total population when calculating 70% of it. This directly contradicts the given information that 70% of students are men, while 180 represents only the women (30%). Let's verify why their answer of 126 is impossible:

If there were 126 men and 180 women, the total would be:<tool_call>
{
    "name": math_eval,
    "arguments": {"expr": "126 + 180"}
}
</tool_call>
<tool_result>
{
    "name": math_eval,
    "arguments": {"expr": "126 + 180"},
    "result": 306,
}
</tool_result>

With these numbers, men would represent:<tool_call>
{
    "name": math_eval,
    "arguments": {"expr": "126 / 306 * 100"}
}
</tool_call>
<tool_result>
{
    "name": math_eval,
    "arguments": {"expr": "126 / 306 * 100"},
    "result": 41.17647058823529,
}
</tool_result>

Only 41.2% of students would be men, not the required 70%. This clearly demonstrates that 126 cannot be the correct answer.
